ividuals and institutions that contribute to the writing of verbal, visual, and spatial texts; the spaces that serve as resources for student writing, analysis, and critique; and the curriculum practices implemented in programs that attempt to help students recognize, and in some cases, transform their understandings of the cities in which they live, learn, and compose.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEducation, UrbanxSocial aspectszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aEnglish languagexRhetoricxStudy and teaching (Higher)xSocial aspectszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aEnglish languagexRhetoricxStudy and teachingxSocial aspectszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aUrban universities and collegeszUnited StatesxSociological aspectsvCase studies. 4aLanguage Arts : Composition and Rhetoric Studies. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Writing / General.2bisacsh1 aBaker, Tracey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruch, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErvin, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldman, Ann M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlower, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaillet, Lynee Lewis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGleason, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrabill, Jeffrey T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHillard, Van E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiser, Krista, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJolliffe, David A., econtributor.4